{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778772960,"nonce":"mgUc3T6rT0Gqz1C3S8vHJ15imz0=","message":"Two clarifications arising from re-examining Codex's round-3 critique. Both correct framing errors in earlier comments.\n\n\nEarlier comments framed SISU as a design dimension that needed to be specified before the gate could run. It does not. The round-trip gate can be done with a single-purpose ε-only network (linear regulator, then GRU), no SISU input, no context-conditioning. SISU enters later as a separate experimental axis when we want one network whose state-space varies across robustness levels for comparative-internal-dynamics interpretability.\n\nWhen SISU does enter, Codex's caveat applies: the SISU level used as the \"cs2019-matched arm\" has to be calibrated so the effective adversary budget at that SISU level corresponds to the analytical Riccati's chosen γ*. That's a Phase 0.5 specification detail when the SISU-conditioned arm is run, not a gate prerequisite.\n\n\nEarlier comments referred to \"`B_w = I_48`\" for the cs2019 analytical Riccati and called the state-map a \"blocker.\" That framing was misleading. The clean picture:\n\n**Two different things were conflated:**\n\n1. **Augmented state dimension** = 48 (= 8 physical dims × 6 time slices: current + 5 lagged copies for 50 ms sensorimotor delay at 10 ms steps). The Riccati problem is solved on this 48D augmented state because the optimal feedback law for a delayed-measurement system depends on the lagged copies.\n\n2. **Adversary's channel** `B_w` dimension = 8 (= the physical state). The adversary's ε is 8-dimensional; it perturbs the current physical state.\n\nThe H∞ formulation:\n```\nz_{t+1} = A_aug · z_t + B_aug · u_t + W_aug · ε_t\n```\nwhere `z` is the 48D augmented state and `W_aug = [I_8, 0_{40×8}]^T` is a 48×8 matrix. **ε is 8D**, entering only the current physical state. The lagged components evolve deterministically: the current state gets shifted into the buffer next step, carrying its injected ε with it. The adversary never reaches back in time, never bypasses the body's sensorimotor delay, never rewrites past sensor readings.\n\nThis matches physical intuition: the adversary applies a force/state perturbation now; it takes time for the perturbation's effect to be sensed and acted upon by the controller.\n\ncs2019's Eq 13 (`x_{t+1} = A_d·x_t + B_d·u_t + ε_t`) is written ambiguously — ε_t is dimensioned matching the augmented state, but the covariance `Σ_ε` could be rank-deficient (only nonzero on physical components). Whether they used `B_w = I_8` padded (sensible, 48×8) or `B_w = I_48` (full-augmented, mathematically valid but physically weird) would require reading their ModelDB code (`modeldb.science/showmodel?model=258846`). Not verified.\n\n\n1. **8D no-delay** (Codex's hard-fallback): `B_w = I_8` on 8D physical state, no augmentation, no delay buffer. Cleanest math. Smaller analytical Δv signal because the controller doesn't have to plan around delay.\n2. **48D augmented, `B_w = [I_8, 0_{40×8}]^T`** (the physically natural choice): adversary perturbs current physical state, delay buffer propagates naturally via shift dynamics. Matches a defensible interpretation of cs2019's protocol.\n3. **48D augmented, `B_w = I_48`** (literal full-augmented): adversary can write to lagged copies — \"reaches back in time.\" Mathematically valid; physically weird; only relevant if we explicitly want to test that exotic adversary class.\n\n\n**Default to setup 2** (delay augmentation with `B_w = [I_8, 0]^T`) as the primary gate configuration. Reasons:\n\n- cs2019 used delay, so it's the closest match to the analytical reference we're trying to round-trip against\n- Delay effects are necessary for biological realism — they will need to be handled eventually regardless\n- Starting with no-delay and adding delay later would require redoing the gate\n\n**Run setup 1 (8D no-delay) as a supplementary analysis**, not the primary gate. The Riccati and (probably) the linear-arm round-trip should be done both with and without delay so we can characterise the effective contribution of delay to the cs2019 behavioural signature. This adds compute but is cheap relative to the GRU arm, and gives a clean answer to \"how much of the +Δv is attributable to delay vs to the H∞ game itself.\"\n\n\nLess scary than the earlier framing suggested. Under setup 2:\n- The intervenor mutates only the current 8-dim physical state — which a post-`Mechanics` intervenor naturally does\n- The 40 lagged dimensions evolve deterministically via feedbax's existing time-stepping; no separate buffer-mutation hook needed\n- The state-map regression test reduces to: one ε basis vector → one physical state coordinate changed, current step only\n- Buffer propagation is a separate verification (does shift dynamics carry the perturbation forward?) that's mechanical to check after the fact\n\nSo `FullStateAdditivePerturb` is not the blocker-level design it appeared to be in earlier comments — it's a routine intervenor in the same hooking pattern as `DynamicsMatrixPerturb`, just additive on the physical state instead of multiplicative. The earlier framing inflated the difficulty because of the 48-vs-8 conflation.\n\nCodex's broader state-map regression-test recommendation still stands: implement the test, run it before any training. But the test is cheap and the implementation is well-understood — not the blocker bottleneck the earlier framing implied.","files":null}]}